      "writtenOn": "2026-04-15T01:04:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "A lot of my complaint here is the cruft that comes in that isn\u0027t really directly part of the interface proper...type traits, allocator traits, internal redblack trees.\n\n\nI agree that I would expect the diffs in size to slow down, but that\u0027s really more of a measure of the amount of stuff in the C++ standard that hasn\u0027t been made part of our ABI yet 😊. \n\nI wonder if it makes sense to filter things that come from internal headers. Maybe we can filter off of something like:\n```\n      \u0027NameSpace\u0027 \u003d\u003e \u0027std\u0027,\n      \u0027PrivateABI\u0027 \u003d\u003e 1,\n```\n\n\nmy point being that I don\u0027t really care if one of the std library symbols gets brought in, really only if the function signatures on our public API changes, afaict we\u0027re not terribly worried about true ABI breakages (this was an argument I made against using C++ for this, and andrew informed me that we\u0027re not terribly worried about 100% ABI compatibility).\n\nI guess I\u0027d like @andrew@codeconstruct.com.au\u0027s input on this, when he\u0027s able. It isn\u0027t terribly pressing, but the amount of stuff coming into gcc dump\u0027s on the two major commits so far make it more of a maintenance burden than it is a tool to spot breakages.\n\nIIRC since our main distribution method for this library is part of a unified deployment model, does it make sense at some point to just make this a header only library? That seems to be how 90% of C++ projects deal with this problem. This clearly isn\u0027t a short term solution. The bonus here is that it absolves us from needing to worry about backwards compat in a super meaningful way, there\u0027s no stale .so sitting around to break for the C++ interface. The con is of course, everything normally involved in a header only lib.",
      "parentUuid": "ccf53fe3_d62fe344",
      "revId": "6316c7a3287ac3ca327cf12e24a52933349cef56",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
